```

##### ENVIRONMENT 
Is Empty
```

```
##### CONFIGURATION

```
group IPV4 {
    hold-time 180;
    graceful-restart 1200;
    family {
       ipv4 flow;
    }
   neighbor 10.0.0.2 {
      router-id 10.0.0.1;
      local-address 10.0.0.1;
      local-as 1764;
      peer-as 1764;
      flow {
         route {
            match {
               source 10.255.255.11/32;
               destination 10.11.255.255/32;
               destination-port =80 >=10&<=15;
               protocol >=tcp;
               tcp-flags =1;
            }
            then {
                extended-community 0x80060000005f5e10;
            }
         }
      }
   }
}


```

##### SUMMARY
(sorry - this may seem a little stupid way of configuring exabgp)
When setting the flowspec rate-action via an extended community (not via the rate-limit keyword) like in the configuration pasted above (0x8006 = traffic-rate action) the community that is advertised to the neighbor is always 0x8006000000000000 (traffic-rate:0:0 = discard)

##### STEPS TO REPRODUCE
Use the above configuration and verify the extended-community that the neighbor receives.

##### EXPECTED RESULTS
Send the same extended-community to the neighbor as configured

##### ACTUAL RESULTS
the extended community advertised is always 0x8006000000000000

##### IMPORTANCE
Is somehow a corner-case when it comes to configuring exabgp (since traffic-rate-limit can be expressed as rate-limit within exabgp but results in a extended-community being advertised to peers).

